THE FALSE FLAGS
A Skyrim One-Shot Adventure

ADVENTURE PROFILE
Title: The False Flags
 Location: Riverwood & White River Bridge
 Party Size: 4 Players + 1 NPC Companion (Hirt)
 Tier: Adept (4-5 AP)
 Duration: 2-3 Hours
 Goal: Obtain a Stamped Imperial Writ to pass the Thalmor blockade and continue north

ADVENTURE SUMMARY
The B-Team (Kyboh, Zach, Ava, and Megan) plus their new companion Hirt are traveling north from Falkreath, searching for the real Obsidian Lanterns. Their journey is halted at the White River Bridge by a Thalmor checkpoint—a "Green Line" fortification that requires official Imperial documentation to pass.
Forced to turn back into Riverwood, the party discovers a group of bandits called the Crimson Blades posing as the famous Obsidian Lanterns. These imposters have a Forged Imperial Writ they're using to impress locals and extort free lodging. The party must expose the frauds, acquire the Writ, and use it to bluff their way past the Thalmor—or fight their way through.
This adventure features:
Social Investigation (proving the imposters are fakes)
Infiltration (stealing the Writ from the bandits' camp)
High-Stakes Deception (bluffing a master interrogator)
Combat Breakout (escaping through a magical barrier)

PART 1: THE BLOCKADE
Time: 10-15 Minutes
 Goal: Establish the obstacle and force the party into Riverwood
THE SCENE
The party has been traveling north along the main road from Falkreath for the better part of a day. The journey has been tense—Hirt walks with them now, the hulking Nord's presence both comforting and unsettling. His blood still burns in his veins, and he scratches at his arms constantly, but he's proven himself a capable ally.
As the road winds through pine forests and crosses over babbling streams, the landscape gradually opens up. Ahead, you can see the bridge—a massive stone span crossing the White River, wide enough for two carts to pass side-by-side.
But something is wrong.
READ ALOUD:
"The White River Bridge rises before you, its ancient stones gleaming in the afternoon sun. But where there should be open road, there are barricades. Heavy wooden posts have been driven into the ground on both sides of the bridge, creating a bottleneck. Behind them stand soldiers in golden armor—Thalmor Justiciars, at least eight of them, backed by robed wizards.
At the center of the bridge itself, you can see something shimmering in the air—a translucent dome of magical energy that arcs from one side of the river to the other, sealing the passage completely.
A line of travelers has formed—merchants with loaded carts, farmers with packhorses, even a few armed sellswords. All of them are being turned away. As you watch, a Nord woman argues with the Justiciar Captain at the checkpoint. She's holding up papers, gesturing angrily. The captain barely glances at them before shaking his head.
'Not sufficient,' you hear him say in accented Tamrielic. 'Turn back. The bridge is closed to unauthorized traffic.'
Hirt stops walking beside you. His breathing has grown heavier, and when you glance at him, you see his hand has moved instinctively to the woodcutter's axe at his belt. His eyes are fixed on the golden armor with an intensity that makes the air feel dangerous."
THE INTERACTION
When the party approaches the checkpoint, they're met by Justiciar Talmor, a stern-faced Altmer in immaculate golden armor. He looks them over with obvious disdain.
Justiciar Talmor: "State your business. Quickly."
The party can respond however they wish, but the answer is always the same:
Justiciar Talmor: "I see. And do you carry a Stamped Imperial Writ authorizing your passage through checkpoints under Aldmeri jurisdiction?"
(If they lie and say yes, he'll demand to see it immediately.)
Justiciar Talmor: "Then you are not authorized. The bridge is closed. Turn back to Riverwood and acquire proper documentation from the Imperial administration in Solitude. Next!"
KEY INFORMATION
If the party asks questions or attempts persuasion (Guile check), they can learn:
What documents are acceptable: "A Stamped Imperial Writ bearing the seal of General Tullius or a senior Legate. Anything less is insufficient."
Why the checkpoint exists: "By the terms of the White-Gold Concordat, the Aldmeri Dominion has the right to secure key strategic positions during times of instability. A dragon has been sighted. The Empire has proven incapable of maintaining order. We are maintaining it for them."
How long it will be here: "Until the crisis is resolved. Weeks. Months. However long is necessary."
THE COMPLICATION: HIRT
If Hirt is visible and not actively hiding:
Roll a d20 secretly. On a 1-5, Justiciar Talmor's eyes linger on Hirt for just a moment too long. He doesn't say anything, but there's recognition there—or at least suspicion. Make a note of this. It will matter later.
THE RAIL
The party cannot fight their way through here. There are too many Justiciars, the magical ward is too strong, and the Thalmor have ranged support. This is a brick wall, not a challenge.
Make this clear: "The checkpoint is heavily fortified. Eight Justiciars in golden armor, three wizards maintaining the ward, and crossbowmen on the high banks. You could try to fight, but you'd be attempting to assault a fortified military position with superior numbers and magical support. That way lies death."
The party must turn back to Riverwood.

PART 2: THE SLEEPING GIANT INN
Time: 30-40 Minutes
 Goal: Meet Delphine, discover the imposters, and gather evidence
SCENE 1: THE ENTRANCE
READ ALOUD:
"Riverwood is a quiet lumber town nestled in the valley between steep mountain ridges. The smell of cut pine fills the air, and you can hear the rhythmic thunk-thunk-thunk of axes biting into wood from the mill by the river.
The Sleeping Giant Inn is easy to find—it's the largest building in town aside from the trading post. Smoke rises from its chimney, and you can hear voices and laughter from inside. Loud voices.
As you push open the door, the noise hits you like a physical force. A group of six people are seated at the main table near the fireplace, drinking heavily and talking even more heavily. They're armed and armored, but their gear looks... mismatched. Scuffed. Like it was assembled from different sources rather than purchased as a set.
Behind the bar, a woman in her forties wipes down mugs with mechanical precision. She has short brown hair, sharp eyes, and the bearing of someone who's seen too much of the world to be impressed by loud drunks. She glances up as you enter, and her gaze lingers on each of you for just a fraction of a second before returning to her work.
A massive Nord woman wearing a dented Imperial helmet that's too small for her head slams her tankard down, bellowing in the worst Cyrodiilic accent you've ever heard: 'And ZAT is 'ow we saved ze Jarl wiz TACTICAL GENIUS!'
Beside her, an enormously fat Khajiit in fur armor drags his claws down the furniture with theatrical scraping sounds, purring: 'This one has punched many dragons, yes?' before immediately reaching for another chicken leg.
Up in the rafters, a Bosmer woman draped in a tattered black cloak whispers loudly: 'The shadows know your secrets...' She's smeared soot on her face like war paint, but she's sweating, so it's running down her cheeks in streaks.
A Dunmer man waves a walking stick with a glowing crystal tied to the top, declaring: 'I am the ASH-MAKER! Behold my power!' He casts Flames—a tiny flicker barely brighter than a candle—and looks offended when no one gasps.
A young Nord crouches behind a massive Dwarven shield, peering over the rim nervously: 'I am the... um... unbreakable shield! Of the Lanterns!'
And moving between tables is a blonde Nord woman in priestess robes, offering blessings: 'May Kynareth guide you, child. A small donation for the temple?' Her smile is warm, but her eyes are calculating every coin purse in the room.
Behind the bar, a middle-aged Nord innkeeper looks like his soul has been slowly crushed over the past two days."
THE IMPOSTERS
The Crimson Blades are in full performance mode. They're trying to impress the handful of locals scattered around the common room, and they're doing a terrible job of it.
"DAVINIA THE QUEENSLAYER" (Actually Ingrid the Loud)
Visual Description: Ingrid is a mountain of a woman—easily six feet tall and built like a beer barrel wrapped in muscle and fat. She's squeezed into a suit of stolen Steel Armor that clearly wasn't made for her frame; the chest plate doesn't close properly, the pauldrons sit at odd angles, and you can see her grimy undershirt peeking through the gaps. Perched atop her head at a jaunty (and ridiculous) angle is a dented Imperial officer's helmet, the kind worn by garrison commanders, not field soldiers. Her blonde hair has been braided in an attempt at Imperial fashion, but it's coming undone.
The Performance: She's attempting a Cyrodiilic accent—the refined speech of Imperial nobility—but it sounds like someone strangling a goose. She keeps dropping into her natural Nord growl mid-sentence, then overcorrecting with exaggerated rolled R's and elongated vowels. Every few minutes, she slams her tankard down hard enough to make the table jump, sloshing ale everywhere, and bellows some variation of: "And ZAT is 'ow we saved ze 'igh Jarl wiz tactical GENIUS and also VIOLENCE!"
Key Details:
She's wearing a fancy scroll case on her belt—this is where the Forged Imperial Writ is kept (when she's at the inn)
She keeps adjusting the helmet because it's too small and gives her a headache
She refers to everyone as "ze brave common folk" in her terrible accent
She's the loudest person in the room by a significant margin
What She's Drinking: Cheap mead, but she keeps demanding "ze finest Cyrodiilic brandy" that Orgnar doesn't stock

"KYBOH THE PUNCH-CAT" (Actually Ma'dran the Wide)
Visual Description: Ma'dran is a Khajiit who has clearly never missed a meal in his life. His fur is a dusty orange color, matted and unkempt, and his belly strains against the leather straps of his Heavy Fur Armor—armor that looks like it was designed for a bear, not a person. His face is round, his whiskers droop, and his eyes have the glazed look of someone three drinks past their limit. He's adorned himself with cheap jewelry—brass rings on every claw, a tarnished copper chain around his neck, and what appears to be a child's toy crown wedged between his ears.
The Performance: Ma'dran has positioned himself at the corner of the table where he can reach the most food. He's currently "sharpening his claws" on the inn's furniture—dragging his claws down the wooden chair back with loud, theatrical scraping sounds that make everyone in the room wince. Between scrapes, he speaks in the third person with exaggerated gravitas: "This one has punched many dragons. This one's fists are registered as deadly weapons in three holds. This one is very dangerous, yes?" He then immediately ruins the effect by reaching for another chicken leg.
Key Details:
He keeps trying to flex, but his armor is so tight it restricts his movement
He's stolen Orgnar's entire stock of sweetrolls and has them piled next to his plate
He hisses at people who get too close to "his" food
Despite his claims of being "faster than lightning," he moves very slowly and gets winded easily
What He's Drinking: Skooma (watered down) mixed with milk, which he claims "enhances the claws"

"SAIJAH THE GHOST" (Actually Anariel the Fleet-Footed)
Visual Description: Anariel is a slight Bosmer woman, genuinely agile and nimble, but utterly failing to project the aura of a mysterious assassin. She's perched on one of the inn's exposed rafters like a nervous bird, her legs dangling over the edge. She's wearing dark leather armor that's actually quite well-made—probably the only genuine piece of equipment among the group—but she's draped a tattered black cloak over it in an attempt to look more "shadowy." Her face is smeared with what appears to be chimney soot in an attempt at war paint, but she's sweating, so it's running down her cheeks in streaks.
The Performance: Every few minutes, Anariel speaks from the rafters in a breathy, theatrical whisper that's somehow still loud enough for everyone to hear: "The shadows know your secrets... they whisper to me of your fears..." She'll then go silent for exactly thirty seconds (she's counting in her head) before delivering another "cryptic" pronouncement: "Death comes on silent wings... probably." She's trying to look mysterious and dangerous, but mostly she looks like someone who climbed up there and is now too scared to climb down.
Key Details:
She has a Hunting Bow, but the string is loose and she hasn't actually drawn it in days
She keeps shifting position on the rafter because it's uncomfortable, ruining her "still as death" pose
When nervous, she forgets to whisper and speaks in her normal, slightly high-pitched voice
She's genuinely good at climbing and hiding—that's the only real skill she has
What She's Drinking: Nothing. She's too high up to safely drink. She's very thirsty and regrets her life choices.

"ALFONSO THE ASH-MAKER" (Actually Faryl Atheron)
Visual Description: Faryl is a Dunmer man in his late twenties with the gaunt, hungry look of someone who's spent too long studying and not enough time eating. His robes are dark blue (or were once—now they're more of a smoke-stained grey), and the edges are genuinely singed, though he did that himself with a candle to create "battle damage." He carries a walking stick that has an orange glowing crystal jammed into the top with twine and tar—it looks like a child's craft project, not a wizard's staff. His dark grey skin is smudged with ash (also self-applied), and his red eyes have the manic gleam of someone who really, really wants you to think he's dangerous.
The Performance: Faryl waves his "staff" around dramatically every time he speaks, nearly setting fire to the curtains twice. His dialogue is peppered with grandiose declarations: "Do not test me, mortal! I have walked through the fires of Red Mountain! I am destruction incarnate! I am the ASH-MAKER!" He'll then cast Flames—a pitiful little flicker of fire that barely illuminates his hand—and act like he's just summoned an inferno. If anyone looks unimpressed, he gets defensive: "That was merely a FRACTION of my power! You should be grateful I showed restraint!"
Key Details:
He knows exactly two spells: Flames and Sparks, both Novice level
His "staff" is literally a stick with a glowing rock tied to it
He keeps a small pouch of ash on his belt to throw dramatically when he makes "threats"
He's a failed apprentice from House Telvanni who got kicked out for incompetence
Despite his bluster, he's genuinely terrified of actual combat
What He's Drinking: Flin (Dunmer liquor), which he claims "enhances his connection to the primal flames"

"ORION THE SHIELD" (Actually Hadring the Slow)
Visual Description: Hadring is a young Nord man, barely into his twenties, with the soft features of someone who's never been in a real fight. He's hiding—yes, hiding—behind a massive Dwarven Shield that he found somewhere and can barely lift. The shield is authentic Dwemer craftsmanship, far too valuable for someone like him to own, and clearly looted from a ruin. He's propped it against the table and is literally crouching behind it, peering over the top rim like a child playing soldier. He's wearing patched Hide Armor that's two sizes too big, and his sword—a basic Iron Sword—leans against the wall where he can't reach it without standing up (which he won't do).
The Performance: Hadring speaks from behind the shield in a voice that's trying to sound deep and heroic but comes out as a nervous squeak: "Stand behind me! I am the... the unbreakable shield! Of the... um... the Lanterns! The Obsidian ones!" He keeps adjusting his position because his legs are cramping from crouching, which makes the shield wobble. Occasionally, one of the other Crimson Blades will shout something threatening, and Hadring will flinch visibly, pulling the shield tighter against himself. If asked about his heroic deeds, he stammers through half-remembered stories that clearly belong to someone else.
Key Details:
The Dwarven Shield is the only valuable item he owns, and he refuses to put it down
He's genuinely scared of combat and will be the first to surrender if a fight breaks out
He joined the Crimson Blades because he thought being a bandit would be safer than being a farmer
Despite his cowardice, the shield is real and actually provides good protection
What He's Drinking: Water. He's too scared to get drunk in case something bad happens.

"DANICA THE PURE" (Actually Ysolda the Opportunist)
Visual Description: Ysolda is a Nord woman in her thirties with sharp, calculating eyes and a smile that never quite reaches them. She's wearing stolen Priestess Robes of Kynareth—genuine temple vestments, likely taken from a raid or bought from a fence. She's done her best to look the part: her blonde hair is pulled back in a simple braid, she wears a wooden holy symbol around her neck (carved by Hadring, not blessed by anyone), and she carries a gnarled wooden staff that looks appropriately humble and sacred. Unlike the others, she's not drunk—she's nursing the same cup of wine she started with two hours ago, staying sharp.
The Performance: Ysolda moves through the common room with practiced grace, stopping at tables to offer "blessings" in a soft, benevolent voice: "May the winds of Kynareth guide you, child. And perhaps... a small donation to the temple? For the orphans, of course." She punctuates her requests with gentle touches on shoulders and warm smiles, all while her eyes calculate exactly how much coin each mark is carrying. She'll "bless" drinks by waving her hand over them and muttering nonsense in a language she made up, then charge five septims for the service. When the other Crimson Blades get too rowdy, she gently "reminds" them to maintain their heroic dignity—not because she cares about dignity, but because loud drunks don't pay as well as impressed believers.
Key Details:
She's the smartest member of the group and the de facto planner
She's a genuine con artist with years of experience
Unlike the others, she doesn't believe her own lies—she's just here for the money
She has a small collection of "holy relics" (worthless junk) that she sells to gullible pilgrims
If things go bad, she'll betray the others without hesitation to save herself
What She's Drinking: Expensive Alto Wine (paid for by "donations"), sipped slowly

ORGNAR THE INNKEEPER
Orgnar (the innkeeper) is behind the bar, looking like a man whose soul has been slowly crushed. He's a middle-aged Nord with thinning hair, permanent worry lines, and the exhausted expression of someone who's been screamed at in broken Cyrodiilic for forty-eight hours straight. His apron is stained, his hands are raw from washing dishes, and he flinches every time Ingrid slams her tankard.
If the party approaches him:
Orgnar: (in a low, desperate whisper) "Welcome to the Sleeping Giant. What can I get you? And please... please... keep it down. Those 'heroes' have been here for two days. They've run up a tab I'll never see paid. They've eaten everything. Ingrid threatened to 'tactically relocate my face' when I asked about payment. I can't get rid of them. The guards won't help—they're scared. I just want them gone."
(He glances toward Delphine at the other end of the bar, then back to the party)
Orgnar: "If you're looking for work... talk to her. She has ideas."
THE KEY OBSERVATION
As the party settles in, they can make a Standard Guile (Perception) check:
Success: You notice that "Davinia" has a fancy-looking scroll case at her belt. It's sealed with red wax bearing an Imperial eagle—the kind of case used for official documents.
Failure: You don't notice the scroll case yet, but Delphine will point it out later.
SCENE 2: DELPHINE'S APPROACH
After the party has had a few minutes to observe (or after they approach the bar), Delphine moves closer and speaks in a low, conversational tone that won't carry to the drunks at the main table.
Delphine: "Rough day at the bridge?"
(If the party responds)
Delphine: "Thought so. I saw the Thalmor setting up their checkpoint yesterday. Turning everyone away without proper papers." (She nods subtly toward the imposters) "Those fools have been here for two days, shouting about how they're the 'Obsidian Lanterns' and waving around what looks like an Imperial Writ to get free food and lodging. They're going to get this whole town burned down if they keep drawing attention."
(She leans in closer, her voice dropping even further)
Delphine: "I need them gone. You need their papers. It seems to me we have a shared interest. You help me get rid of them—quietly—and I can help you get what you need to cross that bridge. But first, I need proof they're frauds. Real proof. Ask around town."
THE QUEST
Delphine will provide three leads the party can investigate. They need to gather at least two pieces of solid evidence to convince her.
The Leads:
The Smith's Appraisal - Get Alvor to examine their gear
The Bragging Rights - Interview locals about the imposters' stories
The Stolen Goods - Find the crate they "confiscated" from a merchant
SCENE 3: IF THEY FIGHT AT THE INN
If the party decides to confront the Crimson Blades directly at the inn (before investigating or going to the camp), combat can break out. However, this is messy and has consequences.
The Complication: Fighting in the inn will:
Destroy Orgnar's furniture (he'll be furious)
Alert the entire town (guards will investigate)
Potentially get the party arrested or banned from Riverwood
Make Delphine refuse to help them (she wanted this handled quietly)
If combat begins anyway:
The six Crimson Blades are drunk, which gives them Disadvantage on all attack rolls. However, they outnumber the party and will fight dirty.
The Writ's Location: Even if the party defeats them here, the Writ is NOT on their bodies—it's still at the camp. One of the defeated imposters can reveal this under interrogation.

