FIGHTING THE CRIMSON BLADES: TACTICAL NOTES
Drunk Penalty: All six imposters have Disadvantage on attack rolls due to intoxication. This means they roll twice and take the worse result.
Glass Cannons: Most of them have low HP and will go down quickly if focused.
Chaos Factor: They don't fight as a team. Each one does their own thing, making them easy to divide and conquer.
The Surrender: If three or more of them are defeated, the survivors will surrender immediately. They're bandits, not fanatics.
Interrogation: Once defeated, any of them can be interrogated to reveal:
The Writ is at their camp in the woods
Delphine was asking questions about them earlier
They stole the Writ from a dead courier near Pinewatch weeks ago
Delphine's Reaction: If the party fights them in the inn, Delphine shouts at them:
Delphine: (coldly) "I said quietly. Now the whole town knows there's trouble. The Thalmor will hear about this. And you still don't have your Writ, not on them. Congratulations. You made this harder for everyone. Get out of my bar.”
She won't be friendly anymore.

PART 3: THE INVESTIGATION
Time: 30-40 Minutes
 Goal: Gather evidence proving the Crimson Blades are frauds
LEAD A: THE SMITH'S APPRAISAL
Location: Alvor's Forge (south side of town)
 NPC: Alvor (Gruff Nord blacksmith)
The party must first get a good look at the imposters' equipment. This requires either:
Option 1: A Standard Guile (Observation) check while in the inn to examine their gear without being obvious
Option 2: Engaging them in conversation and asking to see their weapons/armor (automatic success, but requires roleplaying)
Once they have specific details, they can visit Alvor at his forge.
Alvor: "Aye, I heard the 'heroes' were in town. Haven't had time to visit the inn myself—too much work. Why do you ask?"
(If the party describes the gear)
Alvor: (snorts) "That's not hero's equipment. The 'Imperial helmet'? That's a garrison guard's practice helm. A dent? That's from training, a fight wouldn't do that. The 'enchanted staff'? That's a glow crystal stuck on a walking stick. And don't get me started on the 'ancient Nordic blade'—that's a bandit's knife with scratches made to look like runes. Shoddy work. Real heroes take care of their gear. This is cheap junk, freshly polished."
EVIDENCE GAINED: The gear is fake.

LEAD B: THE BRAGGING RIGHTS
Location: Around town (inn, lumber mill, trading post)
 NPCs: Sven the Bard, Hod the Logger, Gerdur the Mill Owner, Camilla Valerius
The imposters have been bragging to different people around town. Each imposter told their own version of events to whoever would listen. The party needs to talk to multiple townspeople and notice the contradictions themselves.
The party can interview locals with a Standard Guile (Persuasion) check:
Success: The local shares the story they were told
Failure: They're too busy or don't want to gossip

INTERVIEW #1: SVEN THE BARD (At the Inn)
Sven: "The big Imperial woman? Oh yes, she's been very... enthusiastic about sharing her tales. She told me they slew a dragon up in Winterhold—on the frozen lake, no less. She positioned a ballista herself and shot the beast right out of the sky with a single bolt. Very dramatic. I'm trying to work it into a ballad, but the details are a bit..."
(He trails off, looking at his notes with a frown)
Sven: "She kept saying 'tactical positioning' and 'military genius.' Said the dragon never stood a chance against Imperial strategy."

INTERVIEW #2: HOD THE LOGGER (At the Lumber Mill)
Hod: "That Dark Elf with the fancy stick? He wouldn't shut up about dragons yesterday. Kept waving that glowing staff around, nearly knocked over my saw. Said he fought a dragon down in the Rift—killed it with fire magic. Called down the flames of Red Mountain, he said. Burned it to ash where it stood."
(He shakes his head)
Hod: "Seemed awfully proud of himself for a mage who can barely light a candle."

INTERVIEW #3: GERDUR (At the Mill)
Gerdur: "The young Nord with the big shield? He came by asking about lumber prices—not that he had any coin. Got to talking, and he mentioned something about a dragon. Said they... talked to it? Negotiated, he said. Offered it something and it just flew away peacefully. He seemed nervous about the whole thing. Kept looking over his shoulder like he was afraid someone would hear him."

INTERVIEW #4: CAMILLA VALERIUS (At the Trading Post)
Camilla: "The priestess blessed my counter this morning—charged me five septims for it, mind you. She told me the most incredible story while she was here. Said the Obsidian Lanterns saved the Jarl of Falkreath from assassins who'd infiltrated his court. She personally tended to his wounds with Kynareth's grace while the others fought. Very heroic."
(She leans in, lowering her voice)
Camilla: "Though between you and me, I'm not sure she's a real priestess. The blessing felt... perfunctory."

INTERVIEW #5: HOD THE LOGGER (Second Conversation)
If the party mentions the Falkreath story to Hod:
Hod: (suddenly angry) "Wait, they said they SAVED the Jarl? That's a damned lie! I was in Falkreath three days ago delivering lumber. The Jarl's dead! Vampires slaughtered him and half his court at some noble's party. The whole hold is in chaos. Those 'heroes' weren't anywhere near it!"

INTERVIEW #6: LUCAN VALERIUS (At the Trading Post)
Lucan: (if asked about the 'heroes') "Don't get me started. Two days ago, I had a shipment ready for Whiterun—medical supplies for the refugee crisis. Bandages, potions, salves. That Imperial woman and the fat Khajiit claimed it was contraband. CONTRABAND! They 'confiscated' it, hauled the whole crate toward the river. I saw them!"
(He's visibly furious)
Lucan: "They waved some official-looking document at me. Said they had 'authority from the High King.' What kind of heroes steal medicine from refugees?"

EVIDENCE GAINED
Once the party has talked to at least three townspeople, they can piece together the contradictions:
Dragon in Winterhold (killed with ballista) vs. Dragon in the Rift (killed with magic) vs. Dragon (negotiated with peacefully)
Saved the Jarl of Falkreath vs. The Jarl is actually dead (from vampires)
Confiscated contraband vs. Stole legitimate medical supplies
The party realizes these "heroes" can't keep their own lies straight.

LEAD C: THE "CONFISCATED" GOODS
Location: The riverbank (south of town, near the bridge)
 Challenge: Finding the hidden crate
The imposters stashed their stolen loot by the river, thinking no one would look there.
The party must make an Standard Agility (Perception) check:
Success: You spot a wooden crate half-hidden under the bridge pilings, covered with a tarp. The crate is stamped with the mark of the Riverwood Trader.
Inside the crate:
Bandages, healing salves, potions of minor healing
Dried food rations (meant for refugees)
A manifest showing this was destined for "Whiterun Relief Efforts"
EVIDENCE GAINED: The "heroes" are stealing humanitarian supplies.

PRESENTING THE EVIDENCE
Once the party has gathered at least two pieces of evidence, they return to Delphine at the inn.
Delphine: (reviewing what they've told her) "Cheap gear. Contradictory stories. Stolen supplies. Yeah, that's enough. They're frauds alright."
(She leans in close)
Delphine: "Here's what I know. They aren't stupid enough to keep anything important on them while they're drunk. They have a camp in the woods south of town—past the mill, near the old logging trail. That's where they'll have their real loot stashed. And that's where your Writ will be."
(She slides a hand-drawn map across the bar)
Delphine: "Go tonight. They're too drunk to notice anyone missing. Get the Writ, get out, and I'll make sure you have a clear path out of town before they wake up and realize what happened."

PART 4: THE CAMP
Time: 30-40 Minutes
 Goal: Infiltrate the bandits' camp and steal the Forged Imperial Writ
THE LOCATION
The Crimson Blades' camp is hidden in the woods about fifteen minutes south of Riverwood, just off an old logging trail. It's small and crude—clearly the work of people who don't expect to stay long.
Layout:
Three Tents: One larger "leader's tent" and two smaller ones
A Central Campfire: Currently burning low
A Weapon Rack: Holding spare weapons and armor
The Prize: A locked chest in the leader's tent
Guards: Three members of the Crimson Blades are on watch. The rest are back at the inn, drunk.
THE APPROACH
The party can approach this in multiple ways:
OPTION 1: STEALTH
The party attempts to sneak past the guards and reach the leader's tent.
Challenge: Each party member must make a Standard Agility (Sneak) check:
Success: You move quietly through the shadows
Failure: You step on a branch, rustle canvas, or otherwise make noise
If two or more party members fail: The guards are alerted. Combat begins.
If only one party member fails: The guards become suspicious and investigate. The party can attempt to hide (another Agility check) or bluff their way out (Guile check).
OPTION 2: COMBAT
The party can choose to engage the guards directly.
Enemies:
3x Crimson Blade Lookouts (see stat block below)
This is a straightforward fight. The guards will try to raise the alarm (shouting), but the main camp is far enough away that the drunken crew at the inn won't hear.
OPTION 3: DECEPTION
The party can attempt to bluff their way into camp, claiming to be allies, new recruits, or delivering a message.
Challenge: Hard (-4) Guile (Deception) check
Success: The guards buy it and let you approach
Failure: They see through the lie. Roll initiative.
THE CHEST
Once the party reaches the leader's tent, they find a locked chest sitting on a bedroll.
The Lock: Requires a Standard Guile (Lockpicking) check
Success: The lock clicks open
Failure: The lock holds. You can try again, but each attempt makes noise
The Trap: The chest is trapped with a spring-loaded poisoned dart.
Detecting the Trap: Standard Guile (Perception) check
 Disarming the Trap: Hard (-4) Agility (Trap Disarming) check
If the trap is triggered:
The dart fires at whoever is closest to the chest
Agility Save (Standard TN) to dodge
On failure: Take 8 Poison Damage
THE PRIZE
Inside the chest:
The Forged Imperial Writ (a convincing fake bearing General Tullius's seal)
200 gold (the Crimson Blades' accumulated "earnings")
A Steel Dagger (Damage 4, Assassin's Blade property)
A Ring of Minor Magicka (Effect: +5 Maximum FP)
Optional Complication: If the party is being very loud or takes too long, one of the drunk Crimson Blades from the inn comes stumbling back to camp to "check on things." This can lead to a humorous encounter or a tense moment depending on how the party handles it.

